om/api/questions/14853/relationships/activeRevision"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7544","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7544"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"packs":{"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7544/packs","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7544/relationships/packs"}},"revisions":{"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7544/revisions","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7544/relationships/revisions"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14853"},"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7544/content","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7544/relationships/content"}},"specialtyTags":{"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7544/specialtyTags","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7544/relationships/specialtyTags"}},"primaryTags":{"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7544/primaryTags","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7544/relationships/primaryTags"}},"contributionTypes":{"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7544/contributionTypes","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7544/relationships/contributionTypes"}},"contributors":{"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7544/contributors","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7544/relationships/contributors"}},"contribution":{"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7544/contribution","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7544/relationships/contribution"}},"myContribution":{"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7544/myContribution","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7544/relationships/myContribution"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"106245"},"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7544/activeRevision","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7544/relationships/activeRevision"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"881"},{"type":"tags","id":"1115"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"}],"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7544/tags","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7544/relationships/tags"}},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18485"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40473"}],"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7544/contributions","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7544/relationships/contributions"}}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"124900","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/124900"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for a skin check. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His parent was diagnosed with melanoma at age 65. He had sunburns regularly as a child with fitzpatrick skin type 2.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. He has multiple naevi on his trunk and limbs. One naevus on his back measures 5 mm in diameter with regular borders and varying shades of brown (image). There is no ulceration or bleeding. It is bigger than the other naevi, however he states it has been present for at least 10 years and shows a photograph of his back 10 years ago which demonstrates a similar pattern to the naevus.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management plan?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Punch biopsy","Cryotherapy","Immediate excision","Sequential digital dermoscopy in three months","Reassurance and review in 12 months"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a larger naevus and has risk factors for melanoma development, including a family history of melanoma, high childhood sun exposure and multiple naevi. The lesion demonstrates concerning features of colour variation, but does not show clear signs of malignant transformation that would warrant immediate excision such as evolution, irregular borders, ulceration, and the patient is of younger age. Older age is one of the strongest risk factors for melanoma. Proof of non-progression is helpful but more reliable would be sequential digital dermoscopy to monitor for earlier malignant changes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESequential digital dermoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E in three months is the most appropriate management. This allows for careful monitoring of any changes in the lesion\u0027s appearance over time. Digital dermoscopy provides standardised imaging that can detect subtle changes that might not be apparent on clinical examination alone. Mole mapping may be another consideration for this patient given that he has multiple naevi which would require ongoing surveillance life long.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate excision\u003C/strong\u003E would be if there were features highly suspicious for melanoma such as asymmetry, irregular borders, colour variegation, diameter \u0026gt;6 mm, and evolution over time (ABCDE criteria). While this lesion has some concerning features as an \u0027ugly duckling\u0027 with being larger than other naevi, it does not meet the threshold for immediate excision - including that it is 5mm in size. Nonetheless, excision should be discussed with the patient as a potential option.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReassurance and review in 12 months\u003C/strong\u003E represents too long an interval given the concerning features and family history. More frequent monitoring is warranted in this high-risk patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPunch biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate for suspicious pigmented lesions as it may sample only a portion of the lesion and compromise future histological assessment if melanoma is present. If biopsy is required, complete excision should be performed. If the lesion is very large, multiple partial incisional biopsies could be done with careful consideration however has potential for missing the diagnosis with partial biopsies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECryotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E is contraindicated for suspicious pigmented lesions as it destroys the tissue, preventing histological examination and potentially masking a melanoma. It may also result in incomplete treatment if a malignancy is present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of atypical naevi requires a balanced approach between monitoring for changes and avoiding unnecessary procedures. Risk factors such as family history, multiple naevi, and concerning morphological features should guide the frequency of follow-up.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Atypical naevi require regular monitoring with sequential digital dermoscopy in high-risk patients.","Clinical features of atypical naevi include size \u003E6mm, irregular borders, and colour variation.","Personal or family history of melanoma increases the risk of malignant transformation in atypical naevi."],"references":["Reddy KK, Farber MJ, Bhawan J, Geronemus RG, Rogers GS. Atypical (Dysplastic) Nevi: Outcomes of Surgical Excision and Association With Melanoma. JAMA Dermatol. 2013;149(8):928\u2013934.  Available at: https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jamadermatology/fullarticle/1695326","Ngan V, Oakley A.  Atypical melanocytic naevus. DermNet NZ.  2003.  Available at: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/atypical-melanocytic-naevus"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"106245"},"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/124900/itemRevision","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/124900/relationships/itemRevision"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questi